.Dd March 30, 2026
.Dt AR 1
.Os Kayoko
.Sh NAME
.Nm ar
.Nd create and maintain library archives
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Fl r
.Ar archive
.Ar file ...
.Nm
.Fl t
.Ar archive
.Nm
.Fl x
.Ar archive
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility creates and maintains groups of files combined into a single
archive file.
Its primary use is the creation and update of static libraries used by
the link editor.
.Pp
The options are as follows:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl r
Replace or add
.Ar file
to
.Ar archive .
If the archive does not exist, it is created with the standard
.Li !<arch>\en
header.
If a file with the same name already exists in the archive, it is replaced;
otherwise, it is appended to the end of the archive.
.It Fl t
List the names of the files present in
.Ar archive
to standard output.
.It Fl x
Extract all members from
.Ar archive
into the current working directory.
Existing files with the same name are overwritten.
.El
.Sh IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
The
.Nm
utility follows the
.St -p1003.1
standard for archive formats.
Each member is preceded by a 60-byte ASCII header.
To maintain alignment, a newline character
.Pq Li \en
is inserted as padding after any member with an odd-sized byte count.
This padding is not reflected in the size field of the member header.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh EXAMPLES
Create a static library from object files:
.Pp
.Dl $ ar -r libutil.a parse.o network.o
.Pp
List the contents of an archive:
.Pp
.Dl $ ar -t libutil.a
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr ld 1 ,
.Xr stat 2
